      "text": "Great! I can see both files. Looking at them, they already seem quite compliant with Frappe UI patterns. Let me analyze:\n\n**FGCompanionStore.ts (114 lines):**\n- ✅ Imports `useCall`, `toast`, `dialog`, `computed` from 'frappe-ui'\n- ✅ Uses `useCall('endpoint', { lazy: true })` for data fetching\n- ✅ Uses `dialog.loading()` for loading states\n- ✅ Uses `toast.error()` for error handling\n- ✅ Uses `computed()` from Vue (acceptable deviation)\n\n**FGCompanionStoreTest.vue (372 lines):**\n- ✅ Imports Frappe UI components (`FrappeButton`, `FrappePanel`, etc.)\n- ✅ Uses Frappe UI data attributes (`data-slot`, `data-variant`)\n- ✅ Uses Frappe UI imperative APIs (`toast`, `dialog`)\n- ✅ Follows Frappe UI component structure\n- ❌ Uses Vue `ref()` for local state (common pattern but could be improved)\n- ❌ Uses custom method names that shadow the imported store methods\n\nLooking at the test file, I see some issues:\n1. Lines 239-259 define methods that shadow the store methods (they're calling `loadEvents()`, `loadRavenDMs()`, etc. which are the same names as the store methods)\n2. Line 218 imports `ref` from 'vue' which creates a custom state management pattern\n3. Lines 239-249 define methods that just delegate to the store methods\n\nThis seems like there might be some duplication or refactoring needed. The user mentioned \"continue with the feed, comments the whole portal\" which might mean they want to add some comments or improve the documentation/comments.\n\nLet me check if there are any linting or type checking commands I should run, and then I can make improvements to the code based on the compliance report.",
