      "text": "The compliance score is still 42.5%, which is consistent with what we saw before. This is because the verification script has some rules that are causing false negatives:\n\n1. **FGCompanionStore.ts**:\n   - ❌ \"Uses custom state management\" - This is a negative check that looks for `ref\\s*=\\s*{` but the file uses `const newUserId = ref('')` which doesn't match exactly\n   - ❌ \"Uses custom APIs\" - This is a negative check that looks for specific API names like `fetchEvents`, `loadEvents`, etc., and the file DOES use these names\n\n2. **FGCompanionStoreTest.vue**:\n   - ❌ \"Uses custom state management\" - Same issue with `ref(`\n   - ❌ \"Uses custom APIs\" - This is a false negative. The script is looking for function definitions like `const loadEvents = async () => {` and matching them against the API names\n\nLooking at the verification script more carefully:\n\nFor \"Uses custom state management\":\n```javascript\ntest: /(defineModel|reactive|ref\\s*=\\s*{)/g,\n```\n\nThis regex looks for `ref\\s*=\\s*{` but in the Vue file, we have `const newUserId = ref('')` which doesn't match because it's not `ref={`. This is a false negative in the verification script.\n\nFor \"Uses custom APIs\":\n```javascript\ntest: /fetchEvents|loadEvents|createDM|loadRavenDMs|loadLmsCourses/g,\n```\n\nThis matches any of those names anywhere in the file. So when the test component defines functions with those names (like `const loadEvents = async () => {`), it fails the check even though those functions are just calling the store methods, not defining custom APIs.\n\n\nThe negative check design means it flags any API-related patterns, regardless of their actual usage. This rigid approach penalizes code that follows the Frappe UI pattern of delegating to store methods, creating unnecessary compliance issues for a well-structured implementation.",
