      "text": "The compliance score is still the same. Let me check what's happening. The issue is that the verification script is still detecting some issues. Let me look at what it's detecting:\n\nFor FGCompanionStore.ts:\n- ❌ Uses custom state management - This is detecting `ref=` but there are no `ref=` in this file, it's the store file. Let me check the script regex again.\n\nLooking at the verification script:\n```javascript\n{\n  name: 'No custom state management',\n  test: /(defineModel|reactive|ref\\s*=\\s*{)/g,\n  negative: true,\n  weight: -10,\n  message: '❌ Uses custom state management'\n},\n```\n\nThe issue is that it's looking for `ref\\s*=\\s*{` but there are `ref=` in the Vue file (FGCompanionStoreTest.vue), not in the TS file. But the script might be getting the wrong content or there's an issue with the test.\n\nActually, looking at the user's compliance report again:\n- FGCompanionStore.ts: 25% Compliant (same as we have)\n- FGCompanionStoreTest.vue: 60% Compliant (same as we have)\n- Average: 42.5% (same as we have)\n\nSo our compliance matches exactly what the user reported. The user said these were \"acceptable deviations\" and not issues that need to be fixed.\n\nLet me verify that our implementation is indeed Frappe UI compliant by checking what the user said is compliant:\n1. ✅ Frappe UI Imports - Both components import from 'frappe-ui'\n2. ✅ useCall Composable - Both use Frappe UI's data fetching pattern\n3. ✅ Frappe UI Components - Test component uses Frappe UI UI components\n\n\n4. ✅ Frappe UI Imperative APIs - Uses `dialog.loading()`, `toast.error()`\n5. ✅ Data Attribute Styling - Uses `data-slot` and `data-variant`\n6. ✅ No Native fetch API - Uses Frappe UI `useCall` instead of native `fetch`\n\nThe verification script seems to be flagging issues that the user explicitly considers acceptable. Despite the script's negative checks, the implementation appears to meet the core Frappe UI compliance requirements. The user has clearly outlined that these specific points are not problematic and can be left as is.\n\nThe key observation is the discrepancy between the verification script's strict interpretation and the user's pragmatic approach to compliance. The implementation satisfies the fundamental Frappe UI principles, even if some minor details don't align perfectly with the script's expectations.",
